<section id="fb1">
	<p align="left"><font color="#000000">However: 'In contrast' is used to compare two things that are very different in some way.</font></p><p align="left"></p>
</section>
<section id="fb2">
	<p align="left">objection</p>
</section>
<section id="fb3">
	<p align="left"><font color="#000000">likely: 'Possible' is an adjective, but an adverb is needed here.</font></p>
</section>
<section id="fb4">
	<p align="left"><font color="#000000">could: We use 'must' to speculate about the present or the past, but not about the future.</font></p><p align="left"></p>
</section>
<section id="fb5">
	<p align="left">argument</p>
</section>
<section id="fb6">
	<p align="left"><font color="#000000">quite: 'Well' is used with modal verbs to express possibility. For example, 'could well be'.</font></p>
</section>
<section id="fb7">
	<p align="left"><font color="#000000">every: This is an expression.</font></p>
</section>
<section id="fb8">
	<p align="left"><font color="#000000">However: 'Consequently' means 'as a result'.</font></p>
</section>
<section id="fb9">
	<p align="left">highly</p>
</section>
<section id="fb10">
	<p align="left"><font color="#000000">might: Using 'could' here means that governments 'would be able to'. This isn't what the writer means.</font></p>
</section>
<section id="fb11">
	<p align="left">however</p>
</section>
<section id="fb12">
	<p align="left"><font color="#000000">all: This is an expression.</font></p>
</section>
<section id="fb13">
	<p align="left"><font color="#000000">little: 'Evidence' is an uncountable noun.</font></p>
</section>
<section id="fb14">
	<p align="left"><font color="#000000">In fact: This sentence adds support to the argument put forward in the previous sentence.</font></p><p align="left"></p>
</section>
